{"title":"Selective 'Selective Prediction': Reducing Unnecessary Abstention in Vision-Language Reasoning","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Selective prediction for vision-language models often over-abstains at low risk tolerance, discarding many correct answers and yielding impractically low coverage.","method":"ReCoVERR is an inference-time framework that verifies a low-confidence VLM prediction by collecting visual evidence that is both reliable and relevant, without additional training. It converts the initial Q–A into a hypothesis and (i) initializes textual evidences from vision tools (e.g., object detections, region captions, captioning), then (ii) iteratively uses an LLM to generate sub-questions that the VLM answers. Evidence is retained as reliable only if the VLM’s calibrated confidence meets a risk-aware threshold (π_VLM ≥ 1−r), and deemed relevant via a defeasible NLI criterion measuring the change in hypothesis entailment between the evidence and its negation; aggregated evidences must meet an NLI entailment threshold to accept the original answer. Across BLIP2, InstructBLIP, and LLaVA-1.5 on A-OKVQA and VQAv2, this increases coverage and recall at fixed risk tolerance (e.g., up to ~20% coverage gains and substantial recall gains), maintaining the risk budget at 20% and slightly exceeding it at 10% (Tables 1–2; §3–§5)."},{"problem":"Generative VLMs lack well-defined, calibrated confidence estimates needed for reliable selective prediction and evidence reliability checks.","method":"The paper introduces a Self-Prompting confidence estimator: after generating an answer, the VLM is re-prompted to answer a yes/no verification, and the next-token probabilities for ‘yes’/‘no’ form the confidence score; this can be further calibrated via Platt scaling trained on held-out data. They compare against token-probability product/mean baselines and select the most calibrated method per model (Self-Prompting for BLIP models; mean token probability for LLaVA-1.5), as validated by lower calibration error on A-OKVQA (Figure 3; §4.2.1; Appendix A). This calibrated confidence is then used both for vanilla selective prediction thresholds and ReCoVERR’s reliability gating (π_VLM ≥ 1−r)."}]}
